ng, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Sussex","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the English county of Sussex, named ‘(territory of) the South Saxons’, from Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>Seaxe</i> ‘Saxons’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eva","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Popular Latinate form of   Eve  , used also as an Anglicization of the Irish name Aoife ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Eva of Sussex was born in 1114, in Falmer, Sussex, England as the daughter of Thomas de Sussex and Dinah Smale. She had at least 1 daughter with Philip De Braose II. She died in 1200, in Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 86."},"et":{"Cir 1114–1200":"1114–1200","1114–1200":"1114–1200","1110–1170":"1110–1170","1130–1170":"1130–1170","–Male":"Surnud","1094–1164":"1094–1164","before 1114":"enne 1114","1114":"1114","1200":"1200","Cir 1114":"1114","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","1130":"1130","1164 ":"1164","1094":"1094","1170":"1170","Falmer, Sussex, England":"Falmer, Sussex, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bra